<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-631-666  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 631 666.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 9 1990 v7 n28 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC plan to free ATandamp;T stirs debate. (Federal CommunicationsCommission)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taff, Anita.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The FCC's proposal to reduce regulation of ATandamp;T is raisingconcerns in the long distance industry.andP;  During March 1990, theFCC began hearings on whether the industry is ready forderegulation.andP;  The commission proposed offering ATandamp;T moreregulatory flexibility, reducing the review process for new ATandamp;Tbusiness services and allowing the company to offer service viacontracts or on a private non-common carrier basis.andP;  The FCC alsosuggests eliminating rules that prevent ATandamp;T from bundlingservices with equipment.andP;  The International CommunicationsAssociation (ICA), a group of corporate telecommunicationscustomers, supports only the proposal that allows ATandamp;T to roll outbusiness services on shorter notice.andP;  According to US SprintCommunications Corp, the FCC wrongly concluded that ATandamp;T is nolonger a monopoly.andP;  MCI Communications Corp is opposed to thecontract and private non-common carrier proposals.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (rules and regulations)MCI Communications Corp. (commercial policy)US Sprint Communications Co. (commercial policy).andO;Ticker:    T; MCIC.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionTelecommunicationsDeregulationCompetitionInternational Communications AssociationTrade and Professional Associations.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>